'''Ōtaki Ontake Shrine''' (王滝御嶽神社) is a shrine located in {{ill|Ōtaki, Nagano|ja|王滝村|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kiso District, Nagano|ja|木曽郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is also known as '''Ōtaki Route Ontake Shrine''' ('''王滝口御嶽神社.''' おうたきぐちおんたけじんじゃ) or '''Ontake Shrine Ōtaki Route''' ('''御嶽神社王滝口,''' おんたけじんじゃおうたきぐち).

It is one of the shrines associated with the {{ill|Ontake-kyō|lt=Mount Ontake faith|ja|木曽御嶽山信仰|12=draft|12=draft}} and is located along the Ōtaki route (王滝口), a southern ascent to the sacred mountain. Another shrine, {{ill|Kurosawa Ontake Shrine|ja|黒沢御嶽神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, exists along the eastern Kurosawa route. The shrine complex consists of an {{ill|Okumiya|ja|奥社|12=draft|12=draft}} at the summit and a {{ill|Satomiya|ja|里宮|12=draft|12=draft}} at the mountain's base.

== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines the following three deities:
* {{ill|Kuninotokotachi|ja|国常立尊|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kuninotokotachi no Mikoto)
* {{ill|Ōnamuchi|ja|大己貴命|12=draft|12=draft}} (Ōnamuchi no Mikoto)
* {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|12=draft|12=draft}} (Sukunahikona no Mikoto)

Other deities enshrined at the site are listed in the sections on the individual shrine halls.

== History ==
The shrine was founded in {{ill|Taihō era|ja|大宝|12=draft|12=draft}} 2 (702) when {{ill|Takane no Michimoto|ja|高根道基|12=draft|12=draft}}, the governor of {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|12=draft|12=draft}}, established the summit shrine (奥社) on {{ill|Mount Ontake|ja|木曽御嶽山|12=draft|12=draft}}.

In {{ill|Hōki era|ja|宝亀|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (774), {{ill|Ishikawa no Asomi Mochiashi|ja|石川朝臣望足|12=draft|12=draft}}, the governor of Shinano, climbed the mountain under the imperial order of {{ill|Emperor Kōnin|ja|光仁天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} to pray for the cessation of plagues.

Over the centuries, various figures have rebuilt the shrine, including:
* {{ill|Shirakawa no Shōshō Shigeyori|ja|白川少将重頼|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Enchō era|ja|延長|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (925)
* A pilgrimage and restoration ordered by {{ill|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|ja|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Ōhō era|ja|応保|12=draft|12=draft}} 1 (1161)
* A rebuilding of the Satomiya shrine at the mountain base in {{ill|Bunmei era|ja|文明|12=draft|12=draft}} 16 (1484) and {{ill|Bunki era|ja|文亀|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (1503)
* {{ill|Yamamura Yoshitoyo|ja|山村良豊|12=draft|12=draft}}, a magistrate of the Kiso region, rebuilt the shrine in {{ill|Kanbun era|ja|寛文|12=draft|12=draft}} 4 (1664)

The site played a key role in the spread of the {{ill|Ontake Pilgrimage|ja|御嶽講|12=draft|12=draft}} movement in the Edo period. {{ill|Kakumyō|ja|覚明|12=draft|12=draft}}, in {{ill|Tenmei era|ja|天明|12=draft|12=draft}} 2 (1782), opened the Kurosawa ascent route, and {{ill|Fukan|ja|普寛行者|12=draft|12=draft}}, in {{ill|Kansei era|ja|寛政|12=draft|12=draft}} 4 (1792), opened the Ōtaki route. These developments allowed more pilgrims to ascend the sacred mountain.

== Shrine Halls ==
* '''Satomiya''' (里宮) - Located at the first station, also called '''Honsha''' (本社), '''Wakamiya''' (若宮), or '''Iwatogongen''' (岩戸権現). Enshrines {{ill|Kuninotokotachi|ja|国常立尊|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōnamuchi|ja|大己貴命|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* '''Jūni Daigongen''' (十二大権現) - Located below the fourth station. Enshrines {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花開耶姫命|1=Konohanasakuya-hime|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* '''Hakkaisan Shrine''' (八海山神社) - Located at the fifth station. Enshrines {{ill|Kunisatsuchi|ja|国狭槌尊|1=Kunisatsuchi-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* '''Mikasa Shrine''' (三笠山神社) - Located at the seventh station on Mikasa Mountain. Enshrines {{ill|Toyokumununo no Mikoto|ja|豊斟渟尊|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* '''Tano-hara Daikokuten''' (田ノ原大黒天) - Located at the seventh station. Enshrines {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主命|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* '''Summit Shrine (Okusha)''' (頂上奥社) - Located at the summit of Mount Ontake. Enshrines {{ill|Kuninotokotachi|ja|国常立尊|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōnamuchi|ja|大己貴命|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== festivals ==
* '''New Year's Day''' - Saitan Festival (歳旦祭)
* '''July 1''' - Opening of the Mountain Festival (開山祭)
* '''July 27–28''' - Main Festival (例大祭)
* '''September (Early)''' - Closing of the Summit Shrine (頂上奥社閉山祭)
* '''November 23''' - Autumn Festival (秋祭)
