'''Ōtaki Ontake Shrine''' (王滝御嶽神社) is a shrine located in {{ill|Ōtaki, Nagano|ja|王滝村|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kiso District, Nagano|ja|木曽郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is also known as '''Ōtaki Route Ontake Shrine''' ('''王滝口御嶽神社.''' おうたきぐちおんたけじんじゃ) or '''Ontake Shrine Ōtaki Route''' ('''御嶽神社王滝口,''' おんたけじんじゃおうたきぐち).

It is one of the shrines associated with the {{ill|Ontake-kyō|lt=Mount Ontake faith|ja|木曽御嶽山信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and is located along the Ōtaki route (王滝口), a southern ascent to the sacred mountain. Another shrine, {{ill|Kurosawa Ontake Shrine|ja|黒沢御嶽神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, exists along the eastern Kurosawa route. The shrine complex consists of an {{ill|Okumiya|ja|奥社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at the summit and a {{ill|Satomiya|ja|里宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at the mountain's base.

== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines the following three deities:
* {{ill|Kuninotokotachi|ja|国常立尊|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Kuninotokotachi no Mikoto)
* {{ill|Ōnamuchi|ja|大己貴命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Ōnamuchi no Mikoto)
* {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Sukunahikona no Mikoto)

Other deities enshrined at the site are listed in the sections on the individual shrine halls.

== History ==
The shrine was founded in {{ill|Taihō era|ja|大宝|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (702) when {{ill|Takane no Michimoto|ja|高根道基|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the governor of {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, established the summit shrine (奥社) on {{ill|Mount Ontake|ja|木曽御嶽山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

In {{ill|Hōki era|ja|宝亀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 5 (774), {{ill|Ishikawa no Asomi Mochiashi|ja|石川朝臣望足|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the governor of Shinano, climbed the mountain under the imperial order of {{ill|Emperor Kōnin|ja|光仁天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to pray for the cessation of plagues.

Over the centuries, various figures have rebuilt the shrine, including:
* {{ill|Shirakawa no Shōshō Shigeyori|ja|白川少将重頼|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Enchō era|ja|延長|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3 (925)
* A pilgrimage and restoration ordered by {{ill|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|ja|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Ōhō era|ja|応保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (1161)
* A rebuilding of the Satomiya shrine at the mountain base in {{ill|Bunmei era|ja|文明|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 16 (1484) and {{ill|Bunki era|ja|文亀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3 (1503)
* {{ill|Yamamura Yoshitoyo|ja|山村良豊|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a magistrate of the Kiso region, rebuilt the shrine in {{ill|Kanbun era|ja|寛文|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 4 (1664)

The site played a key role in the spread of the {{ill|Ontake Pilgrimage|ja|御嶽講|qq=draft|qq=draft}} movement in the Edo period. {{ill|Kakumyō|ja|覚明|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, in {{ill|Tenmei era|ja|天明|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (1782), opened the Kurosawa ascent route, and {{ill|Fukan|ja|普寛行者|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, in {{ill|Kansei era|ja|寛政|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 4 (1792), opened the Ōtaki route. These developments allowed more pilgrims to ascend the sacred mountain.

== Shrine Halls ==
