'''Ōtaki Ontake Shrine''' (王滝御嶽神社) is a shrine located in [[:en:Ōtaki, Nagano|Ōtaki, Nagano]], [[:en:Kiso District|Kiso District, Nagano]], [[:en:Nagano Prefecture|Nagano Prefecture]]. It is also known as '''Ōtaki Route Ontake Shrine''' ('''王滝口御嶽神社.''' おうたきぐちおんたけじんじゃ) or '''Ontake Shrine Ōtaki Route''' ('''御嶽神社王滝口,''' おんたけじんじゃおうたきぐち).

It is one of the shrines associated with the {{ill|Ontake-kyō|lt=Mount Ontake faith|ja|木曽御嶽山信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ontake-kyō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and is located along the Ōtaki route (王滝口), a southern ascent to the sacred mountain. Another shrine, {{ill|Kurosawa Ontake Shrine|ja|黒沢御嶽神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kurosawa Ontake Shrine|qq=|1=Kurosawa  Ontake Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q119929587}}, exists along the eastern Kurosawa route. The shrine complex consists of an {{ill|Okumiya|ja|奥社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okumiya|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 奥宮}} at the summit and a {{ill|Satomiya|ja|里宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Satomiya|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} at the mountain's base.

== Deities ==
The shrine enshrines the following three deities:
* [[:en:Kuni-no-Tokotachi|Kuni-no-Tokotachi]] (Kuninotokotachi no Mikoto)
* {{ill|Ōnamuchi|ja|大己貴命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōnamuchi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大国主|1=Ōkuninushi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q276944}} (Ōnamuchi no Mikoto)
* {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|少彦名命|1=Sukunabikona|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunahikona|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunabikona|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スクナビコナ}} (Sukunahikona no Mikoto)

Other deities enshrined at the site are listed in the sections on the individual shrine halls.

== History ==
The shrine was founded in [[:en:Taiho|Taihō era]] 2 (702) when {{ill|Takane no Michimoto|ja|高根道基|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takane no Michimoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, the governor of [[:en:Shinano Province|Shinano Province]], established the summit shrine (奥社) on {{ill|Mount Ontake|ja|木曽御嶽山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mount Ontake|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 御嶽山|1=Mount Ontake|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1754806}}.

In [[:en:Hōki|Hōki era]] 5 (774), {{ill|Ishikawa no Asomi Mochiashi|ja|石川朝臣望足|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikawa no Asomi Mochiashi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, the governor of Shinano, climbed the mountain under the imperial order of [[:en:Emperor Kōnin|Emperor Kōnin]] to pray for the cessation of plagues.

Over the centuries, various figures have rebuilt the shrine, including:
* {{ill|Shirakawa no Shōshō Shigeyori|ja|白川少将重頼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shirakawa no Shōshō Shigeyori|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in {{ill|Enchō era|ja|延長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enchō era|qq=|1=Enchō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q97379316}} 3 (925)
* A pilgrimage and restoration ordered by {{ill|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|1=Emperor Go-Shirakawa|2=ja|3=後白河天皇|qid=Q317984|ja|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|1=Emperor Go-Shirakawa|2=ja|3=後白河天皇|qid=Q317984|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Go-Shirakawa|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in [[:en:Ōhō|Ōhō era]] 1 (1161)
* A rebuilding of the Satomiya shrine at the mountain base in [[:en:Civilization|Bunmei era]] 16 (1484) and [[:en:Bunki|Bunki era]] 3 (1503)
* {{ill|Yamamura Yoshitoyo|ja|山村良豊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamamura Yoshitoyo|qq=|1=Yamamura Takatoyo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11469484}}, a magistrate of the Kiso region, rebuilt the shrine in [[:en:Kanbun (era)|Kanbun era]] 4 (1664)

The site played a key role in the spread of the {{ill|Ontake Pilgrimage|ja|御嶽講|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ontake Pilgrimage|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} movement in the Edo period. {{ill|Kakumyō|ja|覚明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kakumyō|qq=|1=Kakumyo Tayubo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11630332}}, in [[:en:Tenmei|Tenmei era]] 2 (1782), opened the Kurosawa ascent route, and {{ill|Fukan|ja|普寛行者|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 御嶽山|1=Mount Ontake|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1754806}}, in [[:en:Kansei|Kansei era]] 4 (1792), opened the Ōtaki route. These developments allowed more pilgrims to ascend the sacred mountain.

